==Vertebrates==
===Birds=== {| class="wikitable" |- ! Rank ! Animal ! Notes |- |1|| [[American woodcock]] {{convert|5|mph|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victorialodging.com/recreation/birding/small-big-fast-slow |title=Smallest Bird, Largest Bird, Fastest Bird, Slowest Bird - Birds of a Feather B&B |location=48.423129;-123.47255 |publisher=Victorialodging.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-08}}</ref> || The American woodcock has been timed flying at 5&nbsp;mph without stalling during [[courtship display]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetravelalmanac.com/lists/animals-slowest.htm |title=The World's Slowest Animals |publisher=Thetravelalmanac.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-08}}</ref> |}
===Reptiles=== {| class="wikitable" |- ! Rank ! Animal ! Notes |- | 1 || [[Galapagos tortoise|Giant Galapagos tortoise]] {{convert|1|mph|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/life/Gal%C3%A1pagos_tortoise |title=BBC Nature - Galápagos giant tortoise videos, news and facts |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-02-08}}</ref> || The Galapagos tortoise can be as slow as 0.23 miles per hour on land. In the water, Galapagos tortoises can move much faster than this. |}
===Fish=== {| class="wikitable" |- ! Rank ! Animal ! Notes |- | 1 || [[Seahorse]] {{convert|5|ft|cm|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://animals.nationalgeographic.com/animals/fish/sea-horse/ |title=Seahorses, Seahorse Pictures, Seahorse Facts - National Geographic |publisher=Animals.nationalgeographic.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-08}}</ref> || The [[dwarf seahorse]] swims at about 0.01&nbsp;mph, making it the slowest fish in the world. They are found in shallow tropical and temperate waters throughout the world. Unlike most other fish, they are monogamous and mate for life. Rarer still, they are among the only animal species on earth in which the male bears the unborn young. <ref>[[Guinness World Records]] (2009)</ref> |}
==Invertebrates==
===Mollusks=== {| class="wikitable" |- ! Rank ! Animal ! Notes |- | 1 || [[Banana Slug]] {{convert|0.000023|m/s|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/life/Gastropoda |title=BBC Nature - Snails and slugs videos, news and facts |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-02-08}}</ref> || The banana slug is said to be the slowest mollusk in the world, as its average speed is only approximately 0.000023&nbsp;m/s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hypertextbook.com/facts/1999/AngieYee.shtml |title=Speed of a Snail |publisher=Hypertextbook.com |date= |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> |}
